<|startoftext|>Question:How can I help a girl that's been through a horrible experience.?
Answer:If she's a young, attractive woman like yourself, there are many things to help her cope. You could try to spend time with her in group time with another woman and a few more. 

But her needs are more than what she may have. You really need to let her know that if she needs someone, you do, and if not, then try to be good to them. 

Talk to her, tell her that your situation will never go back to what it was. If there is a problem, ask for help. Tell her you need to break the news to her about this.

Ask her if she is happy with her past. And if she's not, then talk to her about it, and ask if you can see it on her. Maybe you could just say how you feel for her, and if you want her to feel that way. 

Tell her that it's alright to accept, but she has to realize how bad it may be. She'll appreciate you so much. She'll realize when the time comes to stop, she has to take it. Maybe she can talk to you, talk to a counselor. Maybe even someone who works with kids. Maybe you can give her your wisdom. The more you talk to her and hear from you, the more she'll realize something, or she'll come to some sort of realization. If that's not possible, start having a talk with someone on the other team. 

It sounds like you may have a problem with her past, but you have to really want to help her make the best of this experience. Give her the chance to see what kind of person she has in her life. Talk with her about the situation. 

If she doesn't understand, I would encourage your efforts, but she may be afraid to ask you for help. Ask her, don't you think if you had done this to her for no one, and you needed to break your heart by hurting her? She may not understand and maybe she's scared too, but if you tried to help her it's better for her to come into your life and understand you. Make her want to be with you for who you are.

Good luck, and Happy Thanksgiving!<|endoftext|>
